<subSubSection pageId="117" pageNumber="717" type="description">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[696,954,1162,1196]" pageId="117" pageNumber="717">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 220 mm, S OY o/ tail 130 mm, ear 19 mm, hindfoot 43 mm. | No specific data are available for body weight. The Guadalcanal Giant Rat is the second smallest species in the distinctive genus 
<taxonomicName box="[180,271,1320,1354]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Uromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="117" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Uromys</taxonomicName>
. Pelage is short and soft, with longer bristly guard hairs. Dorsal pelage is reddish brown, being browner near head, redder near rump, and grayer as it fades to ventral pelage on the side; ventral pelage is grayish white with grayunderfur. Feet are very broad and of a dull white coloration. Ears are very small and rounded; vibrissae are long. Tail is very short (59% of head-body length), naked, has fine scaling, and is monocolored black. Skull is longer and narrower than that of the King Giant Rat (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1888" box="[97,181,1561,1590]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Uromys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="117" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="rex">U. rex</taxonomicName>
), and with narrower molars than in the Emperor Giant Rat (
<taxonomicName box="[1033,1202,1561,1590]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Mus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="117" pageNumber="717" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="imperator">U. imperator</taxonomicName>
).
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
